plores the Canadian-Cuban relationship from 1959 to the present day. The essays in this volume reflect upon the past but also explore the internal issues and external forces that will continue to influence the Canada-Cuba association in the years to come.Many of this volume's contributors draw upon newly declassified sources and original interviews, providing unique insight into the historical, economic, and political realities affecting the Canada-Cuba connection. Featuring twelve original essays by a variety of scholars as well as a short memoir by former Canadian Ambassador to Cuba, Mark Entwistle, this important interdisciplinary collection calls into question past understandings of the Canadian-Cuban relationship. It is a must-read for anyone interested in Canadian and Cuban history of the last half-century, and the dynamics of North American politics more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aDonaghy, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEntwistle, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalloran, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirk, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlepak, Hal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMckenna, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolinaro, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunton, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRitter, Archibald R.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSheinin, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVogt, David, econtributo